Step 2: Merge the population data with the state name data

  1. Read in the state name .csv file from the URL below into a dataframe named abbr (for abbreviation) make sure to use the read_csv() function from the tidyverse package:
    https://intro-datascience.s3.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/statesInfo.csv

  1. To successfully merge the dataframe pop with the abbr dataframe, we need to identify a column they have in common which will serve as the key to merge on. One column both dataframes have is the state column. The only problem is the slight column name discrepancy in pop, the column is called state and in abbr State. These names need to be reconciled for the merge() function to work. Find a way to rename abbrs State to match the state column in pop.
abbr <- abbr %>% rename_at('State', ~'state')  # rename 'State' to 'state' in the abbr dataframe
  1. Merge the two dataframes (using the state column from both dataframes), storing the resulting dataframe in dfNew.
# create a new dataframe using merge() and dataframes pop and abbr. R will merge these dataframes based on existing
# columns with the same name.
dfNew <- merge(x=pop, y=abbr)
  1. Review the structure of dfNew and explain the columns (aka attributes) in that dataframe.

Step 4: Group by State

  1. Use group_by and summarise to make a dataframe of state-by-state population. Store the result in dfSimple.
library(dplyr)

dfSimple = dfNew %>% group_by(state) %>%
                    summarise(population = sum(population))
glimpse(dfSimple)
## Rows: 51
## Columns: 2
## $ state      <chr> "Alabama", "Alaska", "Arizona", "Arkansas", "California", "
## $ population <dbl> 1279813, 300950, 4691466, 787011, 27910620, 3012284, 123981
  1. Name the most and least populous states in dfSimple and show the code you used to determine them.
largest_pop <- which.max(dfSimple$population)  # get the index of the largest population and save it to variable largest_pop
dfSimple$state[largest_pop]  # display the state at the index with the largest population
## [1] "California"
smallest_pop <- which.min(dfSimple$population)  # get the index of the smallest population and save it to variable smallest_pop
dfSimple$state[smallest_pop]  # display the state at the index with the smallest population
## [1] "Vermont"

Step 5: Create a map of the U.S., with the color of the state representing the state population

  1. Make sure to expand the limits correctly and that you have used coord_map appropriately.
dfSimple$state <- tolower(dfSimple$state)

states <- map_data("state")
mergedData <- merge(states, dfSimple, all.x=TRUE, by.x="region", by.y="state")

ggplot(mergedData)+
  geom_polygon(data=mergedData, aes(x=long,y=lat,group=group, fill=population))+
  expand_limits(x=mergedData$long, y=mergedData$lat)+
  coord_map()+
  ggtitle("Population of the U.S. by State")
